01:33:26,200 --> 01:33:28,690
that if you measure one of

2566
01:33:28,690 --> 01:33:31,180
the components of spin of sigma,

2567
01:33:32,580 --> 01:33:36,440
and also the same component for the other one,

2568
01:33:36,440 --> 01:33:37,460
they'll be opposite.

2569
01:33:38,240 --> 01:33:40,340
Because it doesn't tell you much if

2570
01:33:40,340 --> 01:33:42,440
you measure the x component of this spin

2571
01:33:42,440 --> 01:33:43,920
and the y component of that spin,

2572
01:33:43,920 --> 01:33:45,200
that doesn't tell you much.

2573
01:33:45,320 --> 01:33:47,150
But it does tell you that if you

2574
01:33:47,150 --> 01:33:48,980
measure the same component of either of them,

2575
01:33:49,040 --> 01:33:50,040
they will come out opposite.

2576
01:33:50,700 --> 01:33:51,180
Yeah?

2577
01:33:52,300 --> 01:33:53,940
This is Bell's theorem,

2578
01:33:53,940 --> 01:33:54,880
the job number.

2579
01:33:55,200 --> 01:33:55,680
So,

2580
01:33:55,680 --> 01:33:57,420
I mean,

2581
01:33:57,420 --> 01:33:59,290
he's dealing with a system where

2582
01:33:59,290 --> 01:34:01,160
these two spins are emitted in opposite.

2583
01:34:01,160 --> 01:34:03,240
And it seems like it would

2584
01:34:03,240 --> 01:34:05,320
be an up-down kind of state.

2585
01:34:05,480 --> 01:34:06,100
Is that right,

2586
01:34:06,100 --> 01:34:06,600
or is that...

2587
01:34:06,600 --> 01:34:06,920
No,

2588
01:34:06,920 --> 01:34:09,510
the kind of states that

2589
01:34:09,510 --> 01:34:12,100
Bell dealt with were entangled states,

2590
01:34:12,100 --> 01:34:13,320
up-down minus down-up.

2591
01:34:13,820 --> 01:34:15,240
It's exactly what he's dealt with.

2592
01:34:17,660 --> 01:34:18,100
Yeah.

2593
01:34:19,820 --> 01:34:22,880
Will any interaction lead to a state like this?

2594
01:34:23,740 --> 01:34:24,180
This?

2595
01:34:24,200 --> 01:34:24,640
Yeah,

2596
01:34:24,640 --> 01:34:26,250
almost any interaction between the spins

2597
01:34:26,250 --> 01:34:27,860
will lead to a state like that.

2598
01:34:29,460 --> 01:34:29,900
Um...

2599
01:34:31,200 --> 01:34:31,640
Yeah,

2600
01:34:31,640 --> 01:34:32,180
but...

2601
01:34:32,860 --> 01:34:35,480
Did you say it's a statistical correlation?

2602
01:34:36,060 --> 01:34:36,500
Yes,

2603
01:34:36,500 --> 01:34:38,320
it's a statistical correlation that,

2604
01:34:38,320 --> 01:34:38,660
um...

2605
01:34:41,920 --> 01:34:42,360
Look,

2606
01:34:42,360 --> 01:34:43,480
at this le...

2607
01:34:43,480 --> 01:34:44,700
To some extent,

2608
01:34:44,700 --> 01:34:49,880
it's similar to a trivial observation.

2609
01:34:50,660 --> 01:34:51,200
You know,

2610
01:34:51,200 --> 01:34:53,450
the way I like to phrase it is I

2611
01:34:53,450 --> 01:34:55,700
have a penny and a dime in my pocket.

2612
01:34:56,640 --> 01:34:57,080
Alright?

2613
01:34:57,540 --> 01:34:59,140
I put my hand in my pocket,

2614
01:34:59,140 --> 01:34:59,700
I take them out,

2615
01:34:59,700 --> 01:35:00,420
I don't look at them.

2616
01:35:00,420 --> 01:35:01,300
Without looking at them,

2617
01:35:01,300 --> 01:35:03,180
I give one to Alice and one to Bob,

2618
01:35:03,680 --> 01:35:05,090
and then I tell Alice

2619
01:35:05,090 --> 01:35:06,500
and Bob to take off and,

2620
01:35:06,500 --> 01:35:07,300
you know,

2621
01:35:07,300 --> 01:35:09,690
go to the moon and go

2622
01:35:09,690 --> 01:35:12,080
to wherever you want to go.

2623
01:35:13,000 --> 01:35:15,040
Then it's going to be the case

2624
01:35:15,040 --> 01:35:17,080
that if Alice looks at her coin,

2625
01:35:17,080 --> 01:35:19,840
she instantly knows what Bob's coin is,

2626
01:35:19,840 --> 01:35:20,100
right?

2627
01:35:21,220 --> 01:35:21,900
She sees,

2628
01:35:21,900 --> 01:35:22,620
if I got a dime,

2629
01:35:22,620 --> 01:35:23,280
he's got a penny.

2630
01:35:23,740 --> 01:35:24,920
If I got a penny,

2631
01:35:24,920 --> 01:35:25,740
he's got a dime.

2632
01:35:26,620 --> 01:35:27,020
Uh...

2633
01:35:27,560 --> 01:35:28,900
That in itself...

2634
01:35:28,900 --> 01:35:30,800
is not surprising.

2635
01:35:31,000 --> 01:35:31,700
There's nothing,

2636
01:35:31,700 --> 01:35:32,260
uh...

2637
01:35:32,580 --> 01:35:33,640
In the past,

2638
01:35:33,640 --> 01:35:34,360
they were together.

2639
01:35:34,580 --> 01:35:36,600
Some correlation was established.

2640
01:35:36,800 --> 01:35:37,460
What was the correlation?

2641
01:35:37,920 --> 01:35:41,260
The correlation was a correlation

2642
01:35:41,260 --> 01:35:44,600
that if Alice has a dime,

2643
01:35:44,600 --> 01:35:48,520
then Bob has a penny,

2644
01:35:48,520 --> 01:35:50,020
and vice versa.

2645
01:35:50,300 --> 01:35:52,460
No other possibilities were possible.

2646
01:35:53,100 --> 01:35:53,940
Right?

2647
01:35:54,800 --> 01:35:56,840
So it was a correlation

2648
01:35:56,840 --> 01:35:58,880
between Alice's coin and Bob's coin.

2649
01:35:58,880 --> 01:36:01,140
And it was an anti-correlation.

2650
01:36:01,880 --> 01:36:03,770
If we called heads and

2651
01:36:03,770 --> 01:36:05,660
tails plus one and minus one,

2652
01:36:06,580 --> 01:36:08,960
then if Alice was plus one,

2653
01:36:08,960 --> 01:36:10,080
Bob is minus one.

2654
01:36:10,220 --> 01:36:11,700
But the opposite is also possible.

2655
01:36:11,820 --> 01:36:12,800
They don't know in advance.

2656
01:36:14,320 --> 01:36:15,060
And yet,

2657
01:36:15,060 --> 01:36:16,580
when Alice is far away

2658
01:36:16,580 --> 01:36:18,100
and when Bob is far away,

2659
01:36:18,100 --> 01:36:19,300
Alice looks at her coin,

2660
01:36:19,300 --> 01:36:21,420
and she instantly knows what Bob's is.

2661
01:36:22,160 --> 01:36:23,320
I assure you,

2662
01:36:23,320 --> 01:36:25,840
that does not violate the special theory of relativity.

2663
01:36:28,960 --> 01:36:33,060
And this kind of correlation is a...

2664
01:36:34,520 --> 01:36:37,340
This is called Einstein-Rosen-Podolsky correlation,

2665
01:36:37,340 --> 01:36:39,100
or entanglement.

2666
01:36:40,900 --> 01:36:42,460
This is the quantum version of

2667
01:36:42,460 --> 01:36:44,020
that same nickel and dime story,

2668
01:36:44,020 --> 01:36:45,100
penny and dime story.

2669
01:36:46,020 --> 01:36:48,140
Real nickels and real properties.

2670
01:36:48,500 --> 01:36:48,560
Yeah.

2671
01:36:48,740 --> 01:36:49,280
No,

2672
01:36:49,280 --> 01:36:50,640
there is certainly a difference.

2673
01:36:50,860 --> 01:36:52,060
There is certainly a difference.

2674
01:36:52,160 --> 01:36:54,220
But just the idea that by

2675
01:36:54,220 --> 01:36:56,280
looking at something at one place,

2676
01:36:56,280 --> 01:36:58,860
you instantly know something that you didn't know before.

2677
01:36:58,860 --> 01:36:59,710
And then you have a second

2678
01:36:59,710 --> 01:37:00,560
to go about the other place.

2679
01:37:01,000 --> 01:37:02,940
That's just statistical correlation.

2680
01:37:03,260 --> 01:37:05,540
It's a tremendously common thing in physics.

2681
01:37:05,720 --> 01:37:06,980
There's nothing special about it.

2682
01:37:07,599 --> 01:37:08,440
The question is,

2683
01:37:08,440 --> 01:37:10,860
what is it that's special

2684
01:37:10,860 --> 01:37:13,280
and different about this entanglement?

2685
01:37:13,780 --> 01:37:16,620
And that's where John Bell found something interesting.

2686
01:37:17,020 --> 01:37:19,040
He didn't find non-locality.

2687
01:37:19,140 --> 01:37:20,870
And we're going to talk next

2688
01:37:20,870 --> 01:37:22,600
time about what non-locality means in physics

2689
01:37:22,600 --> 01:37:25,880
and what it was exactly that John Bell found.

2690
01:37:28,860 --> 01:37:30,000
But I'm going to tell you right now,

2691
01:37:30,000 --> 01:37:32,240
it was not non-locality.

2692
01:37:33,639 --> 01:37:36,000
It looks like non-locality,

2693
01:37:36,000 --> 01:37:37,950
and the reason is because

2694
01:37:37,950 --> 01:37:39,900
you're trying to apply classical reasoning.

2695
01:37:40,240 --> 01:37:42,920
What John Bell said is you

2696
01:37:42,920 --> 01:37:45,600
can't apply classical reasoning to quantum systems.

2697
01:37:45,880 --> 01:37:47,160
That's what it came down to.

2698
01:37:47,300 --> 01:37:49,180
Quantum systems are quantum mechanical,

2699
01:37:49,180 --> 01:37:52,380
and if you try to apply classical reasoning,

2700
01:37:53,019 --> 01:37:55,340
you're going to find inconsistencies.

2701
01:37:56,440 --> 01:37:58,220
I can say it another way.

2702
01:37:58,220 --> 01:37:59,140
I'll tell you another way.

2703
01:37:59,240 --> 01:38:00,440
Here's a way to say it.

2704
01:38:06,399 --> 01:38:08,780
Imagine you had a computer,

2705
01:38:08,780 --> 01:38:12,020
and you tried to simulate on that computer

2706
01:38:12,020 --> 01:38:14,760
the quantum mechanics of a single spin.

2707
01:38:15,300 --> 01:38:17,060
Now here's the way you would simulate it.

2708
01:38:17,720 --> 01:38:22,080
You would be able to instruct the computer

2709
01:38:22,080 --> 01:38:26,440
to orient its apparatus in an arbitrary direction.

2710
01:38:26,660 --> 01:38:27,100
In other words,

2711
01:38:27,100 --> 01:38:28,160
you would put in coordinates.

2712
01:38:28,220 --> 01:38:29,220
You would put in coordinates for a direction.

2713
01:38:30,320 --> 01:38:32,400
And when you put in the coordinates for the direction,

2714
01:38:33,160 --> 01:38:35,340
the computer would do some calculation,

2715
01:38:36,540 --> 01:38:38,640
appeal to a random number generator,

2716
01:38:39,440 --> 01:38:41,800
and spit out a plus one or a minus one.

2717
01:38:43,520 --> 01:38:46,400
There would be an algorithm that would say

2718
01:38:47,640 --> 01:38:50,360
that if you do it over again immediately,

2719
01:38:51,680 --> 01:38:53,800
that you'll spit out the same number again.

2720
01:38:54,980 --> 01:38:56,260
And that if you do it again,

2721
01:38:56,260 --> 01:38:57,960
you'll spit out the same number again.

2722
01:38:57,960 --> 01:39:00,840
But you might then say,

2723
01:39:01,080 --> 01:39:01,700
all right,

2724
01:39:01,700 --> 01:39:03,120
now let me make it more interesting

2725
01:39:03,120 --> 01:39:08,480
by adding in a mathematical magnetic field,

2726
01:39:08,620 --> 01:39:10,040
which allows the spin to process.

2727
01:39:10,560 --> 01:39:11,580
What would you do?

2728
01:39:11,660 --> 01:39:14,820
You would solve the Schrodinger equation.

2729
01:39:15,500 --> 01:39:17,280
Find out what the state was

2730
01:39:17,280 --> 01:39:19,060
after a little bit of time.

2731
01:39:20,080 --> 01:39:22,360
Calculate the probabilities for up and down,

2732
01:39:22,980 --> 01:39:24,960
or whatever you decide to measure.

2733
01:39:25,920 --> 01:39:27,100
Calculate the probabilities.

2734
01:39:27,960 --> 01:39:29,460
Appeal to the random number generator,

2735
01:39:29,700 --> 01:39:33,240
and spit out a number that was statistically

2736
01:39:33,690 --> 01:39:35,660
exactly what you should get on the average

2737
01:39:35,660 --> 01:39:36,940
from quantum mechanics.

2738
01:39:37,600 --> 01:39:39,500
Somebody who came to this computer

2739
01:39:39,500 --> 01:39:42,040
and started playing with it and doing these experiments,

2740
01:39:42,340 --> 01:39:44,680
rotating his apparatus in different directions,

2741
01:39:46,100 --> 01:39:48,900
turning on magnetic fields in other directions,

2742
01:39:49,120 --> 01:39:51,000
weighting various amounts of time,

2743
01:39:51,750 --> 01:39:54,000
and then telling the computer,

2744
01:39:54,180 --> 01:39:55,800
measure this or that component,

2745
01:39:55,800 --> 01:39:59,460
would reproduce exactly quantum mechanics,

2746
01:39:59,600 --> 01:40:01,010
at least to the extent

2747
01:40:01,010 --> 01:40:02,420
that random number generators are possible.

2748
01:40:02,740 --> 01:40:04,120
They're not exactly possible,

2749
01:40:04,280 --> 01:40:06,120
but you can make pretty good random numbers.

2750
01:40:06,700 --> 01:40:07,440
All right.

2751
01:40:07,500 --> 01:40:09,900
So that would be a quantum...

2752
01:40:09,900 --> 01:40:11,680
That wouldn't be a quantum computer.

2753
01:40:11,880 --> 01:40:13,720
That would be a classical computer

2754
01:40:15,900 --> 01:40:17,640
simulating quantum behavior

2755
01:40:18,639 --> 01:40:21,560
where somebody doing a little experiment on it

2756
01:40:21,560 --> 01:40:22,980
could be fooled into thinking

2757
01:40:22,980 --> 01:40:25,780
that it was actually dealing with a single element.

2758
01:40:25,800 --> 01:40:26,180
So you could be doing a quantum experiment

2759
01:40:26,180 --> 01:40:27,000
on a single electron inside the computer

2760
01:40:27,000 --> 01:40:28,720
and doing a quantum experiment.

2761
01:40:28,940 --> 01:40:29,920
You couldn't tell the difference.

2762
01:40:30,520 --> 01:40:31,740
Now the question is,

2763
01:40:31,780 --> 01:40:35,520
could you do the same thing for two spins?

2764
01:40:36,940 --> 01:40:37,900
In particular,

2765
01:40:38,080 --> 01:40:40,500
I want to do the same thing for two spins,

2766
01:40:40,640 --> 01:40:42,300
and I want to do it in such a way

2767
01:40:42,300 --> 01:40:44,060
that one of the spins,

2768
01:40:44,940 --> 01:40:48,140
all of its data is located in one computer,

2769
01:40:49,160 --> 01:40:51,660
and all of the data for the other spin

2770
01:40:51,660 --> 01:40:53,820
is located in the other computer.

2771
01:40:53,820 --> 01:40:55,400
Now I can bring the computers together,

2772
01:40:56,099 --> 01:40:58,600
have wires connecting them and so forth

2773
01:40:58,600 --> 01:40:59,620
for a while,

2774
01:40:59,820 --> 01:41:01,360
do arbitrary things,

2775
01:41:01,640 --> 01:41:04,340
and then cut the wires and separate them.

2776
01:41:05,380 --> 01:41:08,060
Can I simulate

2777
01:41:08,780 --> 01:41:11,900
the quantum mechanics of the two-particle system

2778
01:41:11,900 --> 01:41:14,520
in such a way that it would appear

2779
01:41:14,520 --> 01:41:17,040
that one of the computers contained one particle

2780
01:41:17,040 --> 01:41:20,000
and the other computer contained the other particle?

2781
01:41:20,140 --> 01:41:20,700
Now remember,

2782
01:41:20,700 --> 01:41:22,140
this is a classical computer,

2783
01:41:22,340 --> 01:41:23,700
two classical computers.

2784
01:41:23,820 --> 01:41:25,460
And the answer is that the

2785
01:41:25,460 --> 01:41:27,100
only way you could do it

2786
01:41:27,100 --> 01:41:29,820
would be to have wires connecting the computers

2787
01:41:30,480 --> 01:41:31,840
at all times.

2788
01:41:32,140 --> 01:41:35,300
You could not do it unless the computers

2789
01:41:36,040 --> 01:41:39,020
were capable of interacting directly

2790
01:41:39,780 --> 01:41:40,800
at a distance.

2791
01:41:41,500 --> 01:41:46,360
But that does not mean that the system is non-local.

2792
01:41:46,740 --> 01:41:49,860
Non-local means that signals can be propagated

2793
01:41:49,860 --> 01:41:51,020
from one place to another.

2794
01:41:51,540 --> 01:41:53,660
What it's telling you is you simply can't

2795
01:41:53,820 --> 01:41:56,680
simulate quantum mechanics

2796
01:41:56,680 --> 01:41:59,700
in a local way by a classical computer.

2797
01:42:00,000 --> 01:42:02,560
The logic of quantum mechanics is different.

2798
01:42:02,840 --> 01:42:06,620
It simply does not allow itself to be faked

2799
01:42:07,380 --> 01:42:09,400
by a computer

2800
01:42:09,400 --> 01:42:12,900
unless that computer is connected

2801
01:42:12,900 --> 01:42:16,120
over large distances into everything in the world.

2802
01:42:16,960 --> 01:42:19,720
Quantum mechanics manages to do the same thing

2803
01:42:19,720 --> 01:42:21,960
without having wires connecting things.

2804
01:42:22,980 --> 01:42:23,500
However,

2805
01:42:23,500 --> 01:42:24,660
you could ask the question,

2806
01:42:24,780 --> 01:42:28,040
does that constitute what physicists call non-locality

2807
01:42:28,040 --> 01:42:31,600
or what Einstein would have called non-locality?

2808
01:42:31,780 --> 01:42:32,600
It does not.

2809
01:42:32,680 --> 01:42:34,960
It does not constitute in any way the ability

2810
01:42:34,960 --> 01:42:36,960
to send a message from one place to another.

2811
01:42:37,940 --> 01:42:39,480
But we're going to come to that.

2812
01:42:39,640 --> 01:42:40,500
We'll deal with that.

2813
01:42:42,260 --> 01:42:42,780
No,

2814
01:42:42,780 --> 01:42:46,460
it is fundamentally the inability to simulate

2815
01:42:46,460 --> 01:42:48,780
quantum mechanics by classical computers

2816
01:42:48,780 --> 01:42:51,340
unless the classical computers are hooked up

2817
01:42:51,340 --> 01:42:53,140
in highly non-local ways.

2818
01:42:54,080 --> 01:42:55,060
For more,

2819
01:42:55,060 --> 01:42:57,460
please visit us at stanford.edu.

